{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":148,"record_hash":"sha256:a6abff0415ad6b9c52ae2c9165d111fd24e0bfedf24b6029c62c0a814c7eff49","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:24:02.638Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md\n@@\n The server side of the Agent Trail application is expected to use the\n `but-agentlog` crate to interact with captured data. It should call\n `but-agentlog` read/query/projection primitives rather than reimplementing\n GitMeta key parsing, transcript normalization, target verification, or bounded\n record hydration.\n \n+Even if the Agent Trail application lives in another repository, it should link\n+the real `but-agentlog` code somehow.\n+\n+Possible linkage paths:\n+\n+- short term: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo git\n+  dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n+- local development: use a path dependency from Forge to a local GitButler\n+  checkout\n+- longer term: make `but-agentlog` publishable, or split a smaller\n+  `but-agentlog` read/projection crate if the full GitButler workspace\n+  dependency graph is too heavy\n+\n+Example shape:\n+\n+```toml\n+but-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n+```\n+\n+The important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\n+publication and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation should stay\n+in `but-agentlog`.\n+\n This is still a design-phase decision. Do not start implementing the Forge\n surface until the publication boundary and permissions model are clearer.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:24:02.638Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call